evidence.efficacyEvidence: In a preclinical study, Quizartinib (AC220) reduced white blood cell counts and decreased myeloid cell invasion in a CBL mutant mouse model with myeloproliferative disorder (PMID: 22990016).

references.title: Flt3 inhibitor AC220 is a potent therapy in a mouse model of myeloproliferative disease driven by enhanced wild-type Flt3 signaling.

evidence.efficacyEvidence: In a preclinical study, CHZ868 inhibited proliferation of myeloproliferative neoplasm cells harboring JAK2 V617F , including cells with decreased response to Type I JAK inhibitors following chronic exposure, and decreased mutant allele burden in a mouse polycythemia vera model expressing JAK2 V617F (PMID: 26175413).

references.title: CHZ868, a Type II JAK2 Inhibitor, Reverses Type I JAK Inhibitor Persistence and Demonstrates Efficacy in Myeloproliferative Neoplasms.

evidence.efficacyEvidence: In a preclinical study, Fasudil (HA-1077) selectively inhibited proliferation of CBL and CBLB double knockout hematopoietic stem/progenitor cells in a mouse model of myeloproliferative disorder (PMID: 26177294).

references.title: Fasudil, a clinically safe ROCK inhibitor, decreases disease burden in a Cbl/Cbl-b deficiency-driven murine model of myeloproliferative disorders.

evidence.efficacyEvidence: In a clinical study, Roferon-A (Alpha 2 Interferon) treatment resulted in hematologic response in 100% (31/31) and complete molecular response in 6% (2/31) of essential thrombocythemia (ET) patients harboring CALR mutations (PMID: 26486786).

references.title: Clinical and molecular response to interferon-α therapy in essential thrombocythemia patients with CALR mutations.

evidence.efficacyEvidence: CALR mutations are used in the diagnosis of myeloproliferative neoplasms, especially of essential thrombocythemia and primary myelofibrosis (PMID: 26697989, PMID: 26449662, PMID: 26071474, PMID: 25873496).
